hj_igo wrote:
&gt; Recently I encountered a problem with StrutsTestCase. The following
&gt; code is my Struts Action and its dependent business logic is injected
&gt; by Spring.
&gt; 
&gt; public class ListCourseAction extends Action {
&gt;   private CourseService courseService;
&gt; 
&gt;   public void setCourseService(CourseService courseService) {
&gt;     this.courseService = courseService;
&gt;   }
&gt; 
&gt;   public ActionForward execute(ActionMapping mapping,
&gt;                                ActionForm form,
&gt;                                HttpServletRequest request,
&gt;                                HttpServletResponse response) throws
&gt; Exception {
&gt;     Set allCourses = courseService.getAllCourses();
&gt;     request.setAttribute(&quot;courses&quot;, allCourses);
&gt;     return mapping.findForward(&quot;courseList&quot;);
&gt;   }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; Now I want to test this Action with StrutsTestCase and mock that
&gt; CourseService. But I don&#39;t know how to pass the mock object to my
&gt; action in StrutsTestCase. The only way I have found is to write
&gt; another Spring context config file and program pseudo business logic,
&gt; then inject them into my actions when testing. But I don&#39;t want to do
&gt; my test in that way.
&gt; There must be some kind of dependency between Struts Action and
&gt; business logic, and how do you deal with this case? How do you design
&gt; and test your Struts Actions?

I don&#39;t do Struts, but if I did, I&#39;d simply invoke setCourseService() in 
the test. My guess is that each test wants to pass in a slightly 
differently-behaving implementation of CourseService, anyway.
